AO/EB staining demonstrated that GQDs could induce marked apoptosis in zebrafish embryos (Fig. 4
                        A). There were significant changes between GQDs treated and control zebrafish when the GQDs concentration was above 50 μg/mL (Fig. 4B). Anatomically, these GQDs impaired regions were subcutaneously near to the undeveloped caudal veins, most of which derive from the blood island. Also, the ROS signals were significantly induced in GQDs exposed zebrafish embryos, compared to that in E3 solution. However, the fluorescent values were relatively stable among different concentrations (Fig. 5
                        ).
